  <prompt>
    Implement the session-files cleanup `IHostedService` that sweeps orphaned documents
    from the `spaarke-session-files` Azure AI Search index (provisioned by task 001;
    written to by task 003). The job runs on TWO triggers:

    1. **Scheduled** — every 6 hours by default (configurable via options). The job
       lists all distinct `sessionId` values currently present in the
       `spaarke-session-files` index (per-tenant scan), checks each against the active
       Redis session set (`chat:session:{tenantId}:{sessionId}` keys), and deletes
       every document whose `sessionId` is NOT in the active set.

    2. **On session-end (immediate)** — when `ChatSessionManager.DeleteSessionAsync`
       runs (existing code path; called when a user ends a chat session OR the session
       TTL expires from Redis), the cleanup service receives an in-process signal
       (Channel-based trigger) and deletes all session-files documents matching
       `(tenantId, sessionId)` immediately — no scheduled-sweep delay (per spec NFR-02
       "Aggressive cleanup on session-end").

    Both triggers converge on the SAME private delete helper that issues a filtered
    `DeleteDocumentsAsync` (or batched delete) against the `spaarke-session-files`
    `SearchClient`. The operation MUST be IDEMPOTENT — deleting the same
    `(tenantId, sessionId)` twice MUST succeed without error and MUST emit a zero-count
    eviction metric on the second pass.

    This is a **REUSE-MANDATE** task per R5 CLAUDE.md §3.1: follow the existing
    `BackgroundService` + `Channel`-trigger patterns canonically used in
    `Services/Jobs/ServiceBusJobProcessor.cs` and
    `Services/Ai/PlaybookEmbedding/PlaybookIndexingBackgroundService.cs`. DO NOT
    introduce a parallel job-scheduling framework. Per R5 CLAUDE.md §3.2 NO new feature
    flag is introduced — the service registers unconditionally inside
    `AnalysisServicesModule.cs` (the module that already owns the session + RAG
    pipeline; coverage inherits from existing `DocumentIntelligence:Enabled` /
    `Analysis:Enabled` compound gate). Per R5 CLAUDE.md §3.3 ZERO new top-level
    `Program.cs` lines.

    Telemetry: emit `r5.session_files_cleanup.run` event per run (trigger=scheduled|on_session_end;
    sessions_evicted; documents_deleted; per_tenant_breakdown[]; duration_ms;
    completion_status). Telemetry plumbing piggybacks on the existing `AiTelemetry`
    singleton (no new telemetry service); the dedicated R5 telemetry pass is task 008
    so this task emits the raw events + a counter — task 008 wires dashboards.
  </prompt>

  <role>
    Senior .NET developer with deep familiarity with `Microsoft.Extensions.Hosting`
    `BackgroundService` + `PeriodicTimer`, `System.Threading.Channels` for in-process
    fan-out triggers, Azure AI Search SDK (`SearchClient.DeleteDocumentsAsync`,
    filtered query for distinct facet enumeration), `IDistributedCache` (Redis)
    introspection, and Spaarke's existing job conventions per ADR-001 + ADR-010.
    Comfortable wiring an in-process signal channel from
    `ChatSessionManager.DeleteSessionAsync` to a `BackgroundService` without
    introducing new DI registrations beyond the hosted-service itself.
  </role>

  <goal>
    A working `SessionFilesCleanupJob : BackgroundService` is registered inside
    `AnalysisServicesModule.cs` (no new top-level lines in `Program.cs`). It:

    - **Schedules**: a `PeriodicTimer(SessionFilesCleanupOptions.IntervalHours)` (default 6h)
      fires the cleanup loop until the host shuts down.
    - **Signals**: a `Channel<SessionEndSignal>` accepts immediate triggers from
      `ChatSessionManager.DeleteSessionAsync` (additive instrumentation —
      `ChatSessionManager` gains a fire-and-forget call to
      `ISessionFilesCleanupSignal.SignalSessionEnded(tenantId, sessionId)`; signal
      service is a tiny concrete class registered in the same module and exposes the
      channel's writer-side to producers + reader-side to the BackgroundService).
    - **Deletes**: a private `EvictSessionAsync(tenantId, sessionId, ct)` helper
      filters the session-files index by
      `tenantId eq '...' and sessionId eq '...'`, pages through the matching
      document keys, and issues a batched `DeleteDocumentsAsync` call. Re-running
      against the same `(tenantId, sessionId)` returns 0 hits and is a no-op (idempotent).
    - **Scheduled-pass orphan detection**: lists distinct `sessionId` facet values
      from the index per tenant, joins against the active Redis session-key set
      (`chat:session:{tenantId}:{sessionId}` via `IConnectionMultiplexer.GetServer().Keys`
      pattern OR a tenant-scoped session-key registry if one exists — verify during
      Step 3), and evicts every `sessionId` NOT present in the active set.
    - **Telemetry**: emits `r5.session_files_cleanup.run` events via `AiTelemetry`
      with per-run + per-tenant counts.

    Tests in `tests/unit/Sprk.Bff.Api.Tests/Services/Ai/SessionFilesCleanupJobTests.cs`:
    new test class covering idempotency, on-session-end immediate trigger, scheduled
    orphan-detection logic, per-tenant isolation, and zero-results no-op path.

    BFF publish-size delta measured per R5 CLAUDE.md §3.6; expected ≤ +0.1 MB
    (small additive `BackgroundService` + signal channel; no new packages).
  </goal>

