    <patterns>
      <pattern name="BackgroundService + PeriodicTimer (scheduled-pass shape)" location="src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Jobs/ScheduledRagIndexingService.cs">
        Canonical reference for the scheduled-pass half of this task. Note the
        options binding via `IOptions&lt;ScheduledRagIndexingOptions&gt;`, the
        `_options.Enabled` early-exit, the `_serviceProvider.CreateScope()` per-run
        scope for scoped dependency resolution, the `PeriodicTimer`-equivalent
        `await Task.Delay(interval, stoppingToken)` loop, and the
        `OperationCanceledException` catch-on-shutdown idiom. The R5 cleanup job
        mirrors this shape but: (a) defaults `Enabled` to TRUE (no opt-in flag per
        R5 §3.2); (b) uses `PeriodicTimer` for cleaner cancellation semantics; (c)
        ALSO drains a `Channel&lt;SessionEndSignal&gt;` reader in the same loop via
        `Task.WhenAny(timer.WaitForNextTickAsync, channelReader.WaitToReadAsync)`.
      </pattern>
      <pattern name="Channel-based in-process signal (on-session-end trigger)" location="src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Ai/PlaybookEmbedding/PlaybookIndexingService.cs">
        Canonical reference for the in-process signal half of this task.
        `PlaybookIndexingService` exposes a `Channel&lt;PlaybookIndexingRequest&gt;` with
        an unbounded writer; producers (the trigger endpoint) call
        `.Writer.TryWrite(request)`; the BackgroundService `ProcessQueueAsync` reads
        via `await reader.WaitToReadAsync(ct)` + `while (reader.TryRead(out var req))`.
        R5 cleanup job uses the SAME pattern via a small `SessionFilesCleanupSignal`
        helper class (concrete; registered as singleton inside
        `AnalysisServicesModule`). Helper exposes `ISessionFilesCleanupSignal`
        interface — single allowed seam, justified by `ChatSessionManager` test
        isolation (Tier-1 unconditional service mocking convention).
      </pattern>
      <pattern name="AddHostedService inside AnalysisServicesModule (DI registration)" location="src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Infrastructure/DI/AnalysisServicesModule.cs">
        Line 325 (current): `services.AddHostedService&lt;Sprk.Bff.Api.Services.PlaybookSchedulerService&gt;();`
        is the precedent for adding a hosted service inside the compound-gated
        Analysis registration. The R5 cleanup-job registration goes immediately
        below this line, inside the same `if (analysisEnabled &amp;&amp; documentIntelligenceEnabled)`
        block. Registration block:
        ```csharp
        services.AddSingleton&lt;SessionFilesCleanupSignal&gt;();
        services.AddSingleton&lt;ISessionFilesCleanupSignal&gt;(sp =&gt; sp.GetRequiredService&lt;SessionFilesCleanupSignal&gt;());
        services.Configure&lt;SessionFilesCleanupOptions&gt;(configuration.GetSection(SessionFilesCleanupOptions.SectionName));
        services.AddHostedService&lt;SessionFilesCleanupJob&gt;();
        Console.WriteLine("✓ Session-files cleanup hosted service enabled (R5 task 007, NFR-02)");
        ```
        ZERO new top-level `Program.cs` lines. The compound-gate placement also
        keeps the service OFF when AI is disabled (kill-switch inheritance per R5 §3.2).
      </pattern>
      <pattern name="AiSearchOptions.SessionFilesIndexName (already added by task 003)" location="src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Options/AiSearchOptions.cs">
        Task 003 adds `SessionFilesIndexName` (default `"spaarke-session-files"`).
        The cleanup job consumes this via `IOptions&lt;AiSearchOptions&gt;` — no new
        options property required. If task 003 hasn't merged yet, coordinate via
        the project's parallel-execution group P1-G5 (003 is in P1-G2; 007 is in
        P1-G5 — 003 lands first).
      </pattern>
      <pattern name="Fire-and-forget producer call in ChatSessionManager (mirror Cosmos pattern)" location="src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Ai/Chat/ChatSessionManager.cs">
        Lines 215–231 already show the fire-and-forget Cosmos-persist convention:
        try/catch + `LogWarning` on failure; never throws. The new
        `SignalSessionEnded` call follows the same shape at the end of
        `DeleteSessionAsync`. Inject `ISessionFilesCleanupSignal? _cleanupSignal`
        as a nullable constructor parameter via `GetService&lt;&gt;()` (mirroring the
        existing `ISessionPersistenceService?` null-tolerance) so existing tests
        + the compound-AI-OFF path continue to work without re-wiring.
      </pattern>
      <pattern name="AiTelemetry event emission" location="src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Telemetry/AiTelemetry.cs">
        Use the existing `AiTelemetry` singleton for the
        `r5.session_files_cleanup.run` event. Telemetry instrumentation depth
        (dashboards, cost rollups) is task 008's scope — this task emits the raw
        event + a counter; task 008 wires Application Insights queries.
      </pattern>
      <pattern name="Test conventions for BackgroundService" location="tests/unit/Sprk.Bff.Api.Tests/Services/Ai/Chat/SessionCleanupSecurityTests.cs">
        Existing session-cleanup security tests follow the in-process test
        convention. Test the cleanup job by: (a) instantiating directly (no
        host startup); (b) calling the private/internal `EvictSessionAsync`
        helper via `InternalsVisibleTo` OR by writing to the signal channel and
        invoking the loop body directly; (c) mocking `SearchClient`,
        `IDistributedCache`, `AiTelemetry`. Idempotency tests: invoke
        `EvictSessionAsync` twice; assert second invocation calls
        `SearchAsync` (to enumerate keys) but skips `DeleteDocumentsAsync` when
        results are empty.
      </pattern>
