  <context>
    <background>
      R5 ships a chat-driven "Summarize a Document" vertical slice. Users upload up
      to 20 files per chat session; those files are indexed into the
      `spaarke-session-files` Azure AI Search index (provisioned by task 001;
      written by task 003). When a session ends — either explicitly via
      `ChatSessionManager.DeleteSessionAsync` OR implicitly via Redis TTL expiry —
      the session's indexed documents become orphaned and MUST be evicted (spec
      NFR-02: "Aggressive cleanup on session-end"). The cleanup job owns this
      eviction: scheduled scans catch implicit TTL expirations; the on-session-end
      signal handles explicit deletes immediately.

      Design rationale (design.md §4.2; spec.md Open Decisions): keeping the
      ephemeral session-files index lean prevents AI Search cost creep + keeps
      query-time relevance high. Without active cleanup, an N-week-old session's
      documents would still be searchable for some time after Redis TTL expiry
      (since AI Search indexes don't auto-evict). The cleanup job is the
      operational guarantor of the session-scoped retention contract.

      Per R5 §3.1 reuse mandate, this task uses existing patterns
      (`BackgroundService`, `Channel`, `IOptions`) and adds NO new external
      scheduler dependency. The task is parallel-safe with task 008 (telemetry)
      in P1-G5; together they ship Phase 1's operational guarantees.
    </background>
    <dependencies>
      <dependency task="001" status="dependency">
        Task 001 provisions the `spaarke-session-files` index. Cleanup writes
        DELETE batches to this index — must exist on Spaarke Dev.
      </dependency>
      <dependency task="003" status="dependency">
        Task 003 adds `AiSearchOptions.SessionFilesIndexName` + the indexing
        write path. Cleanup deletes from the same index using the same options
        property. Field-name alignment (`sessionId`, `tenantId`) is task 001's
        schema; this task consumes it.
      </dependency>
    </dependencies>
    <related-work>
      <item>Task 008 (D1-08) is the dedicated R5 telemetry pass — it wires
        dashboards consuming the `r5.session_files_cleanup.run` events this task
        emits. Coordinate event name + field shape with task 008 at PR time.</item>
      <item>Task 009 (D1-09) runs the Phase 1 test consolidation + publish-size
        verification — this task contributes its publish-size measurement to
        the Phase 1 baseline.</item>
      <item>`ChatSessionManager.DeleteSessionAsync` is the canonical session-end
        site for the explicit-end signal. Redis-TTL-driven implicit ends are
        only caught by the scheduled pass (no callback exists for natural
        Redis expiry — the scheduled scan is the only mechanism).</item>
      <item>`PlaybookIndexingBackgroundService` is the closest existing pattern
        (signal-driven `BackgroundService` inside the AI module); follow its
        shape closely.</item>
    </related-work>
  </context>

